===Etymology===
From {{etyl|xno|en}} {{m|fro|revestir}}, {{m|en|revestre}} et al., {{etyl|frm|en}} {{m|frm|revestir}}, and their source, {{etyl|LL.|en}} {{m|en|revestire}}, from {{etyl|la|en}} {{m|la|re-}} + {{m|la|vestīre|to clothe}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|en|/ɹiːˈvɛst/}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|obsolete}} To [[dress]] (a priest or other religious figure) in ritual garments, especially to celebrate Mass or another service.
# To [[reclothe]]; to dress again.
#* '''1590''', Edmund Spenser, ''The Faerie Queene'', II.i:
#*: Her nathelesse / Th'enchaunter finding fit for his intents, / Did thus '''reuest''', and deckt with due habiliments.
# To return (property) to a former owner; to [[reinstate]]
# To invest again with possession or office.
#: ''to '''revest''' a magistrate with authority''
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To take effect again.

